'''John Clayton Mayer'''<ref name=allmusicbio>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/john-mayer-mn0000239827/biography|title=John Mayer Biography|first=Andrew|last=Leahey|publisher=[[AllMusic.com]]|access-date=October 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026001533/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/john-mayer-mn0000239827/biography|archive-date=October 26, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|m|eɪ|.|ɚ}} {{Respell|MAY|ər}}; born October 16, 1977) is an American singer, songwriter, and guitarist.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Hoard |first1=Joel |title=John Mayer: Biography |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/john-mayer/biography |magazine=Rolling Stone |access-date=March 18, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826142006/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/john-mayer/biography |archive-date=August 26, 2017 |date=2001}}</ref> Born and raised in [[Fairfield County, Connecticut]], Mayer attended [[Berklee College of Music]] in [[Boston]], but left   and moved to [[Atlanta]] in 1997 with [[Clay Cook]]. Together, they formed a short-lived two-man band called Lo-Fi Masters. After their split, Mayer continued to play local clubs, refining his skills and gaining a following. After his appearance at the 2001 [[South by Southwest]] festival, he was signed to [[Aware Records]], and eventually to [[Columbia Records]], which released his first [[extended play]] ''[[Inside Wants Out]]''. His following two studio albums—''[[Room for Squares]]'' (2001) and ''[[Heavier Things]]'' (2003)—performed well commercially, achieving [[Music recording certification|multi-platinum]] status. In 2003, he won the [[Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance]] for his single "[[Your Body Is a Wonderland]]".

By 2005, Mayer had moved away from the acoustic music that characterized his early records, and begun performing the [[blues]] and rock music that had originally influenced him as a musician. He collaborated with blues artists such as [[B.B. King]], [[Buddy Guy]], and [[Eric Clapton]]. Forming the [[John Mayer Trio]], he released a live album, ''[[Try!]]'', in 2005 and his third studio album ''[[Continuum (John Mayer album)|Continuum]]'' in 2006. Both albums received positive reviews, and ''Continuum'' earned Mayer a [[49th Annual Grammy Awards|2007]] [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album]]. He also won [[Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance|Best Male Pop Vocal Performance]] for "[[Waiting on the World to Change]]". That album was followed by ''[[Battle Studies (album)|Battle Studies]]'' in 2009, a return to pop, with a Battle Studies World Tour.

After having several controversial incidents with the media, Mayer withdrew from public life in 2010 and began work on his fifth studio album, ''[[Born and Raised (John Mayer album)|Born and Raised]]'', which drew inspiration from the 1970s pop music of [[Laurel Canyon, Los Angeles#History|Laurel Canyon]]. However, the discovery of a [[granuloma]] on his vocal cords delayed the release of the album until May 2012, and forced him to cancel the planned tour. The album received a generally favorable reception, though was less commercially successful than his previous work. Mayer began performing as a singer again in January 2013, and that year released his sixth studio album, ''[[Paradise Valley (album)|Paradise Valley]]'', which incorporates [[country music]] influences. By 2014, he had sold a total of over 20 million albums worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/photos/top-new-acts-since-2000-1403561474-slideshow/| title=USA: Top 20 New Acts Since 2000| website=Yahoo! Music| date= July 8, 2014| last=Grein| first=Paul| access-date=July 10, 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714153307/https://music.yahoo.com/photos/top-new-acts-since-2000-1403561474-slideshow/| archive-date=July 14, 2014| url-status= live}}</ref> His seventh album, ''[[The Search for Everything]]'', a loose concept album based around the theme of a romantic break-up, was released in 2017. Mayer released his latest album, ''[[Sob Rock]]'', inspired by 1980s [[soft rock]] music, in July 2021.

In 2015, three former members of the [[Grateful Dead]] joined with Mayer and two other musicians to form the band [[Dead & Company]].<ref name=deadtour/> It is the latest of several [[Reunions of the Grateful Dead|reunions]] of the band's surviving members since [[Jerry Garcia]]'s death in 1995. The band remains active and its tours have been well received.<ref name= NYT-Launch16>{{Citation |date=February 8, 2016 |title=Dead & Company To Launch 2016 Tour |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |url=http://markets.on.nytimes.com/research/stocks/news/press_release.asp?docTag=201602080700PR_NEWS_USPRX____LA17152&feedID=600&press_symbol=3744685 |access-date=April 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420134946/http://markets.on.nytimes.com/research/stocks/news/press_release.asp?docTag=201602080700PR_NEWS_USPRX____LA17152&feedID=600&press_symbol=3744685 |archive-date=April 20, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name= Nev11.27.A>{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=John |date=December 1, 2015 |title=Review + photos: Dead & Company a tale of two shows in one night at MGM Grand |website=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |url=http://lasvegassun.com/vegasdeluxe/2015/dec/01/review-photos-dead-company-a-tale-of-two-shows-one/ |access-date=April 8, 2016 |quote="With superb guitar skills and strong vocals on several titles ("West L.A. Fadeaway" and "Deal," among them), Mayer continued to win over the army of itinerant Deadheads in the audience Saturday night." |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406132255/http://lasvegassun.com/vegasdeluxe/2015/dec/01/review-photos-dead-company-a-tale-of-two-shows-one/ |archive-date= April 6, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Mayer's secondary career pursuits extend to television hosting, comedy, and writing; he has [[columnist|authored columns]] for magazines such as ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''. He supports various causes and has performed at charity benefits. He is a watch aficionado (with a collection he values in the "tens of millions" of dollars), contributing to the watch site ''[[Hodinkee]]'', and has been on the jury at the ''[[:fr:Grand Prix d'Horlogerie de Genève|Grand Prix d'Horlogerie de Genève]]''.<ref name=wrist>{{cite news| last= Williams| first= Alex |date= April 30, 2015|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/01/fashion/mens-style/john-mayer-watches.html |title= John Mayer's Wrist Is a Wonderland| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323214242/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/01/fashion/mens-style/john-mayer-watches.html |archive-date= March 23, 2017 |work= The New York Times| access-date= May 4, 2015}}</ref>

==Early life==
Mayer was born on October 16, 1977 in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]].<ref name=allmusicbio /> His father, Richard Mayer (b. 1927), was a high-school principal, and his mother, Margaret (''née'' Hoffman; b. 1947), was a middle-school English teacher.<ref name="eliscu">{{cite magazine |last1=Eliscu |first1=Jenny |title=Songs in the Key of Mayer |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/songs-in-the-key-of-mayer-234694/ |magazine=Rolling Stone |access-date=April 15, 2020 |date=November 27, 2003}}</ref><ref name= hip>{{cite journal |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20138163,00.html |title= It's Hip to Be Square| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924150948/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20138163,00.html |archive-date= September 24, 2015| date= October 7, 2002| journal= [[People (magazine)|People]] | volume= 58| number= 15| page= 107}}</ref> He grew up in nearby [[Fairfield, Connecticut|Fairfield]], the middle child between older half-sister Rachel,<ref>{{cite AV media | people =Carl Mayer (@carlwmayer) | date =July 10, 2022 | title =$15 Game Show  —John Mayers family instagram updates | medium =webshow | time =2m40s | location =White Plains, NY | publisher =Instagram }}</ref> older brother Carl, and younger brother Ben.<ref name=Brothers>{{cite web | last= Spillane |first= Sean |date= March 18, 2015|title=Central High School - John Mayer|url=http://bridgeport.ct.schoolwebpages.com/education/components/scrapbook/default.php?sectiondetailid=31898|website=School Web Pages |publisher=CT Post |access-date=February 13, 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060321050346/http://bridgeport.ct.schoolwebpages.com/education/components/scrapbook/default.php?sectiondetailid=31898|archive-date=March 21, 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=John Mayer|journal=[[TV Guide]] |url=https://tvguide.com/celebrities/john-mayer/bio/196620|access-date=August 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826115832/http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/john-mayer/bio/196620|archive-date=August 26, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> His father is [[Jewish]], and Mayer has said that he relates to [[Judaism]].<ref name=Playboy/> As an elementary school student, Mayer became close friends with future tennis star [[James Blake (tennis)|James Blake]], and they played Nintendo together weekday afternoons after school for three years.<ref>{{cite journal| last= Tapper| first= Christina |date= August 23, 2008|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20220809,00.html | title= James Blake on John Mayer: No High School Lothario| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018184225/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20220809,00.html |archive-date= October 18, 2014 |journal= People| access-date= March 23, 2015}}</ref> He attended the [[Center for Global Studies at Brien McMahon High School]] in [[Norwalk, Connecticut|Norwalk]] for his junior year (then known as the Center for Japanese Studies Abroad, a [[magnet school|magnet program]] for learning Japanese).<ref name= "eliscu" />

After watching [[Michael J. Fox]]'s guitar performance as [[Marty McFly]] in ''[[Back to the Future]]'', Mayer became fascinated with the instrument.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Duricka|first=Tamara|last8=!|date=2015-07-03|title='Back to the Future' turns 30: Time sure does McFly|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/herocomplex/la-ca-hc-back-to-the-future-anniversary-20150708-story.html|access-date=2021-02-02|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US}}</ref> When he turned 13 years old, his father rented one for him.<ref>{{cite web| year= 2005|url=https://www.pbs.org/wttw/soundstage/jmayer/bio.htm | work= Soundstage| title= John Mayer with special guest Buddy Guy| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512163150/http://www.pbs.org/wttw/soundstage/jmayer/bio.htm |archive-date= May 12, 2015 | via= [[PBS]].org| access-date= May 31, 2007}}</ref><ref name=AskMen>{{cite web| year= 2005|url=http://www.askmen.com/men/entertainment_100/140c_john_mayer.html | title= Men Of The Week: Entertainment—John Mayer| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080118221108/http://www.askmen.com/men/entertainment_100/140c_john_mayer.html |archive-date= January 18, 2008 | website= AskMen.com| access-date= April 12, 2006}}</ref> A neighbor gave Mayer a [[Stevie Ray Vaughan]] cassette, which cultivated Mayer's love of blues music.<ref name=CU>{{cite news| date= November 6, 2006|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/close-up/mon-nov-6-telecom-spam-attack-john-mayer-881586 | title= Mon Nov 6: Telecom; Spam Attack; John Mayer| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105044240/http://tvnz.co.nz/close-up/mon-nov-6-telecom-spam-attack-john-mayer-881586 |archive-date= January 5, 2016 | publisher= [[TVNZ]] | access-date= December 6, 2006}}</ref>{{cref|a}} According to Mayer, his fascination with Vaughan started a "genealogical hunt" that led him to other blues guitarists, including [[Buddy Guy]], [[B.B. King]], [[Freddie King]], [[Albert King]], [[Otis Rush]], and [[Lightnin' Hopkins]].<ref name=RSGG>{{cite magazine| author-link= David Fricke| first= David |last= Fricke|date= February 22, 2007|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/the-new-guitar-gods-20070222 |title= The New Guitar Gods| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018054537/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/the-new-guitar-gods-20070222 |archive-date= October 18, 2016 | magazine= Rolling Stone| number= 1020| pages= 39–47}}</ref> Mayer started taking lessons from a local guitar shop owner, Al Ferrante, and soon became consumed.<ref name=Hedegaard>{{cite magazine| last= Hedegaard| first= Erik |date= February 4, 2010| title= The Dirty Mind and Lonely Heart of John Mayer| magazine= Rolling Stone| number= 1097| pages= 36–45, 68}}</ref><ref name=Mather>{{cite web| last= Hedegaard| first= Erik |date= March 2008|url=http://www.menshealth.com/celebrity-fitness/article-print.php?102 | title= The Wonder of John Mayer Land| website= menshealth.com| publisher= Rodale| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402100704/http://www.menshealth.com/celebrity-fitness/article-print.php?102 | archive-date= April 2, 2015}}</ref> His singular focus concerned his parents, and they twice took him to see a psychiatrist, who determined him to be healthy.<ref name=Hedegaard/><ref name=Mather/> Mayer says that his parents' contentious marriage led him to "disappear and create my own world I could believe in".<ref name=Hedegaard/> After two years of practice, he started playing at bars and other venues, while still in high school.<ref name=AskMen /> In addition to performing solo, he was a member of a band called Villanova Junction (named for a [[Jimi Hendrix]] song) with Tim Procaccini, Joe Beleznay, and Rich Wolf.<ref name=Hedegaard/><ref name=TW>{{cite web| last= Wallace| first= William |date= January 1, 2005|url=http://www.tweedmag.com/News/Joe_Beleznay_wants_to_be_the_ball.html | title= Joe Beleznay wants to be the ball| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061019032247/http://www.tweedmag.com/News/Joe_Beleznay_wants_to_be_the_ball.html |archive-date=October 19, 2006 |work= Tweed Magazine| access-date= October 30, 2006}}</ref>

When Mayer was 17, he was stricken with [[cardiac dysrhythmia]] and was hospitalized for a weekend. Reflecting on the incident, Mayer said, "That was the moment the songwriter in me was born", and he penned his first lyrics the night he left the hospital.<ref name=RS06>Hiatt, Brian (September 21, 2006), "My Big Mouth Strikes Again". ''Rolling Stone'' (1009): pp. 66–70.</ref> Shortly thereafter, he began suffering from [[panic attacks]], and says he feared having to enter a [[mental institution]].<ref name=Hedegaard/> He continues to manage such episodes with [[anti-anxiety drug|anti-anxiety medication]].<ref name=RS06/><ref name=MandS>{{cite web|url=http://a1135.g.akamai.net/f/1135/18227/1h/cchannel.download.akamai.com/18227/podcast/RICHMOND-VA/WRVQ-FM/johnmayer2.mp3 |title= John Mayer| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127141057/http://a1135.g.akamai.net/f/1135/18227/1h/cchannel.download.akamai.com/18227/podcast/RICHMOND-VA/WRVQ-FM/johnmayer2.mp3 | archive-date= January 27, 2012 | format= MP3 podcast |work= Melissa and Sid| date= March 31, 2008| publisher= [[WRVQ-FM]]}}</ref>

==Career==

===Early career (1996–1999)===
{{See also|Inside Wants Out}}
Mayer considered skipping college to pursue music, but his parents dissuaded him.<ref name=Hedegaard/> He enrolled at the [[Berklee College of Music]] in 1997 at age 19.<ref name=ELLE>Ruth Shaut (2006), "Blues Brother". ''Elle''. (250-251):104.</ref> At the urging of his college friend [[Clay Cook]], they left Berklee after two semesters and moved to Atlanta; there, they formed a two-man band called LoFi Masters, and began performing in local coffee houses and club venues such as [[Eddie's Attic]].<ref name=Berklee>{{cite web| last= Small| first= Mark |year=2005|url=http://www.berklee.edu/bt/172/coverstory.html |title= John Mayer '98: Running with the Big Dogs| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070410200154/http://www.berklee.edu/bt/172/coverstory.html |archive-date= April 10, 2007 |work= Berklee Today| via= Berklee.edu| publisher= Berklee College of Music| access-date= April 23, 2007}}</ref><ref name=AskMen/> According to Cook, they experienced musical differences due to Mayer's desire to move more towards pop music.<ref name=MOA>{{cite news| last= Guthrie| first= Blake |date= November 20, 2003|url=https://atlanta.creativeloafing.com/content-184733-Cover-Story--Mayer-of-Atlanta |title= Mayer of Atlanta: John Mayer plays Philips Arena, and all I got was this lousy cover story| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080110213456/http://atlanta.creativeloafing.com/gyrobase/Content?oid=oid%3A14103 |archive-date= January 10, 2008 | work= [[Creative Loafing]]| access-date= February 17, 2007}}</ref> The two parted ways and Mayer embarked on a solo career.<ref name=Berklee/>

With the help of local producer and engineer Glenn Matullo, Mayer recorded the independent [[Extended play|EP]] ''[[Inside Wants Out]]''. The EP includes eight songs with Mayer on lead vocals and guitars. For the opening track, "Back To You", a full band was enlisted, including the EP's co-producer [[David LaBruyere|David "DeLa" LaBruyere]] on bass guitars.<ref name=MO>{{cite web| last= Alter| first= Gaby |date= April 1, 2007|url=http://mixonline.com/live/tourprofiles/audio_john_mayer_2/ |title= Tour Profile: John Mayer| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904114813/http://mixonline.com/live/tourprofiles/audio_john_mayer_2/ |archive-date=September 4, 2014 | work= Mix| via= mixonline.com| access-date= April 23, 2007}}</ref> Cook had co-written many of the album's songs, including its first commercial single release, "[[No Such Thing (John Mayer song)|No Such Thing]]"; however, his only performance contribution was backing vocals on the song "Comfortable".<ref name=MOA/>

===Major label and commercial success (2000–2004)===
{{See also|Room for Squares|Heavier Things}}

Mayer and LaBruyere performed throughout Georgia and nearby states.<ref name="Graham">{{cite web |last1=Graham |first1=George |title=George Graham Reviews John Mayer's 'Room for Squares' |url=http://georgegraham.com/reviews/jmayer.html |website=georgegraham.com |access-date=July 21, 2019 |date=April 10, 2002}}</ref> Also, as his career coincided with the then-nascent internet music market, Mayer benefited from an online following.<ref name=hay>Hay, Carla (April 6, 2002), "Aware/Columbia's John Mayer Makes 'Room For Squares' A Hit". ''Billboard''. '''114''' (14):22.</ref> Mayer came to the attention of [[Gregg Latterman]] at Aware Records through an acquaintance of Mayer's, a lawyer, who sent Aware his EP.<ref>{{cite news| last1= Wood| first1=Mikael|title=Room at the Top|url=http://www.dallasobserver.com/music/room-at-the-top-6390314|access-date=December 22, 2017 |work= [[The Dallas Observer]] |date= March 28, 2002|quote=I met a great lawyer who was willing to promote me. He sent out my records to labels, and Aware was one of his first ideas. He knew my music well enough to know it was gonna take a smaller label to do it, and he was right. Aware was the label. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222162540/http://www.dallasobserver.com/music/room-at-the-top-6390314|archive-date=December 22, 2017| url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=Mather/><ref>{{cite web| last= Proefrock| first= Stacia |year= 2005 |url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p405816|pure_url=yes}} |title= Biography| work= All Music Guide| access-date= April 23, 2007}}</ref> In early 2001, after including him in Aware Festival concerts and his songs on Aware compilations, Aware released Mayer's internet-only album, ''[[Room for Squares]]''. During this time, Aware concluded a deal with [[Columbia Records]] that gave Columbia first pick in signing Aware artists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awarerecords.com/company.php |title= A Brief History| publisher= Aware Records| access-date= June 12, 2007| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207084321/http://www.awarerecords.com/company.php |archive-date= February 7, 2007 }}</ref> In September, Columbia remixed and re-released ''Room for Squares''.<ref name=malindanewman>{{cite magazine| last= Newman| first= Melinda |date= September 8, 2001| title= The Beat| magazine= Billboard| volume= 113| number= 36| page= 14}}</ref> As part of the major label "debut", the album's artwork was updated, and the track "3x5" was added. The re-release included reworked studio versions of the first four songs from ''Inside Wants Out''.<ref>{{cite web| last= Back| first= Alan | date= June 15, 2001|url=http://www.nique.net/issues/2001-06-15/entertainment/2 |title= John Mayer carves out his own niche with national debut album| website= Nique.net | access-date= June 22, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929132049/http://www.nique.net/issues/2001-06-15/entertainment/2 |archive-date=September 29, 2007 }}</ref>

By the end of 2002, ''Room for Squares'' had spawned several radio hits, including "[[No Such Thing (John Mayer song)|No Such Thing]]", "[[Your Body Is a Wonderland]]", and "[[Why Georgia]]". It also received general praise critically, and Mayer drew comparisons to [[Dave Matthews]].<ref name= Berklee/><ref name=malindanewman/> In 2003, Mayer won a Grammy for [[Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance|Best Male Pop Vocal Performance]] for "Your Body Is a Wonderland".<ref name=Grammyverification>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=%22john+mayer%22&field_nominee_work_value=&year=All&genre=All |title= Past Winners Search| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402133827/http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=%22john+mayer%22&field_nominee_work_value=&year=All&genre=All |archive-date= April 2, 2015 |website= Grammy.com| access-date= March 18, 2015}}</ref> In his acceptance speech he remarked, "This is very, very fast, and I promise to catch up."<ref name=Mather/> He also figuratively referred to himself as being 16, a remark that many mistook to mean that he was 16 years old at the time.<ref name=RSG07>Serpick, Evan (February 2007), "Grammy Preview: John Mayer", ''Rolling Stone'', Volume unknown: p. 32.</ref>

In February 2003, Mayer released a live CD and DVD of a concert in [[Birmingham, Alabama]] titled ''[[Any Given Thursday]]'', which included songs previously not recorded, such as "Man on the Side", "[[Something's Missing (John Mayer song)|Something's Missing]]", and "Covered in Rain". Commercially, the album peaked at number 17 on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart.<ref name="Amazon - Any Given Thursday">{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Any-Given-Thursday-John-Mayer/dp/B000083GLC |title=John Mayer - Any Given Thursday - Amazon.com Music |access-date=28 July 2019 |website=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon.com]] }}</ref> Its accompanying DVD release received conservative—although consistent—praise, with critics torn between his pop-idol image, and (at the time) emerging guitar prowess.<ref name=EW>Browne, David (March 14, 2003), [https://ew.com/ew/article/0,,430023,00.html "Strummer Time"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509233100/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,430023,00.html |date=May 9, 2012 }}. ''Entertainment Weekly''. (700):62.</ref> Erik Crawford of [[AllMusic]] asked, "Is [Mayer] the consummate guitar hero exemplified when he plays a cover of Stevie Ray Vaughan's '[[Lenny (instrumental)|Lenny]]', or is he the teen idol that the pubescent girls shriek for after he plays 'Your Body Is a Wonderland'?"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crawford |first1=Erik |title=Review |url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r626637|pure_url=yes}} |date=June 8, 2007}}</ref><ref>Medsker, David (2003). [https://popmatters.com/music/reviews/m/mayerjohn-any.shtml "Love me, love me, say that you love me..."] Pop Matters. Retrieved June 8, 2007. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061112212945/http://www.popmatters.com/music/reviews/m/mayerjohn-any.shtml |date=November 12, 2006 }}</ref> That summer, Mayer went on the road with [[Counting Crows]] in a tour that spanned 42 dates between July 7 and September 2.<ref>Ault, Susanne (July 12, 2003), [https://books.google.com/books?id=5Q0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA15&lpg=PA15&dq=Mayer,+Crows+Take+Their+Guitars+On+The+Road#v=onepage&q=Mayer%2C%20Crows%20Take%20Their%20Guitars%20On%20The%20Road "Mayer, Crows Take Their Guitars On The Road"]. ''Billboard''. '''115''' (28):15.</ref>

''[[Heavier Things]]'', Mayer's second album, was released in 2003 to generally favorable reviews. ''Rolling Stone, Allmusic,'' and ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' all gave positive, although reserved, feedback.<ref>
MacNeil, Jason (2003).
[https://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/mayerjohn/heavierthings "Heavier Things"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070514200644/http://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/mayerjohn/heavierthings |date=May 14, 2007 }} Metacritic. Retrieved June 4, 2007.
</ref> The album was commercially successful, and while it did not sell as well as ''Room for Squares'', it peaked at number one on the US ''Billboard'' 200 chart. The song "[[Daughters (John Mayer song)|Daughters]]" won the 2005 Grammy for [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]],<ref name=Grammyverification/> and reached #1 on the ''Billboard'' Adult Pop Songs chart<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/artist/304974/john-mayer/chart?page=1&f=343 "John Mayer Chart History – Adult Pop Songs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612232828/http://www.billboard.com/artist/304974/john-mayer/chart?page=1&f=343 |date=June 12, 2016 }}, retrieved February 28, 2016.</ref> and #19 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/artist/304974/john-mayer/chart?page=1&f=379 "John Mayer Chart History – Hot 100] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160613054001/http://www.billboard.com/artist/304974/john-mayer/chart?page=1&f=379 |date=June 13, 2016 }}, retrieved February 28, 2016.</ref> He dedicated the award to his grandmother, Annie Hoffman, who had died in May 2004.<ref>(May 21–22, 2004), [http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/ctpost/obituary.aspx?n=annie-j-hoffman&pid=2250825 "Annie J. Hoffman-Obituary"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017085446/http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/ctpost/obituary.aspx?n=annie-j-hoffman&pid=2250825 |date=October 17, 2015 }}. Legacy.com. Retrieved August 2, 2015.</ref> He also won Best Male Pop Vocal Performance. On February 9, 2009, Mayer told [[Ellen DeGeneres]] that he thought he should not have won the Grammy for Song of the year because he thought that Alicia Keys' "[[If I Ain't Got You]]" was the better song. Because of this, he removed the top half of the Grammy and gave it to Keys, and kept the bottom part for himself. At the 37th Annual [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]] Induction Ceremony in 2006, Mayer received the [[Hal David Starlight Award]].<ref>(2006) [http://www.songwritershalloffame.org/award_recipient_detail.asp?ceremonyId=27&awardRecipientId=150 John Mayer]. Song Writers Hall of Fame. Retrieved September 29, 2006. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061001163422/http://www.songwritershalloffame.org/award_recipient_detail.asp?ceremonyId=27&awardRecipientId=150 |date=October 1, 2006 }}</ref>

Mayer again recorded live concerts across seven nights of his U.S. tour in 2004. These recordings were released to the [[iTunes Store]] under the title ''[[As/Is]]'', indicating that the errors were included along with the good moments. A few months later, a "best of" CD was compiled from the ''As/Is'' nights. The album included a previously unreleased cover of [[Marvin Gaye]]'s song "[[Inner City Blues (Make Me Wanna Holler)]]", featuring a solo from Mayer's supporting act—jazz and blues turntablist [[DJ Logic]]. The album covers of the ''As/Is'' releases feature drawings of [[anthropomorphic]] bunnies.<ref>[http://www.johnmayer.com/bio Bio] JohnMayer.com. Retrieved June 25, 2007. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070720121613/http://www.johnmayer.com/bio |date=July 20, 2007 }}</ref>

===Change in musical direction (2005–2008)===
{{See also|John Mayer Trio|Continuum (John Mayer album)}}
As early as 2002, Chris Willman with ''Entertainment Weekly'' said that Mayer was "more historically savvy, and more ambitious than you'd guess from the unforced earnestness of ''[Room for] Squares''{{-"}}.<ref name=willman>Willman, Chris (August 9, 2002), "Meet John Dough". ''Entertainment Weekly''. (666):36.</ref> However, Mayer was largely associated with the Adult Contemporary and singer-songwriter genres.<ref name=willman/> Fame allowed him access to his early influences, and he began collaborating with blues and jazz artists. He accompanied Buddy Guy in a concert at the Irving Plaza in December 2003.<ref>Fricke, David (February 5, 2004), "Buddy Guy/John Mayer". ''Rolling Stone''. (941):68.</ref> He toured with jazz pianist [[Herbie Hancock]], including a show at the [[Bonnaroo Music Festival]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/61680/herbie-hancock-goes-beyond-jazz|title=Herbie Hancock Goes Beyond Jazz|date=August 24, 2005|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=December 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217105657/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/61680/herbie-hancock-goes-beyond-jazz|archive-date=December 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He also performed on commercial releases, namely, with [[Eric Clapton]] (''[[Back Home (Eric Clapton album)|Back Home]]'', [[Crossroads Guitar Festival]]), [[Buddy Guy]] (''[[Bring 'Em In (Buddy Guy album)|Bring 'Em In]])'', [[John Scofield]] (''[[That's What I Say (John Scofield album)|That's What I Say]]''), and [[B.B. King]] (''[[B. B. King & Friends: 80|80]]''). Although Mayer maintained his reputation as a singer-songwriter, he gained distinction as a guitarist.

Following the conclusion of his ''Heavier Things'' tour, Mayer began working with artists, including those from other genres of music. His voice was sampled on the song "[[Be (Common album)#"Go!"|Go]]" by rapper [[Common (rapper)|Common]], and he appeared on a hidden track called "Bittersweet Poetry" from the [[Kanye West]] album ''[[Graduation (album)|Graduation]]''.{{cref|b}} The collaborations drew praise from rap heavyweights [[Jay-Z]] and [[Nelly]].<ref>Rodriguez, Jason (April 13, 2007). [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1557129/20070413/id_0.jhtml "Shawty's Story: Lloyd Says He Stole From Usher, Loves John Mayer"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070429045605/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1557129/20070413/id_0.jhtml |date=April 29, 2007 }} MTV. Retrieved April 16, 2007.</ref> When asked about his presence in the [[hip hop]] community, Mayer said, "It's not music out there right now. That's why, to me, hip-hop is where rock used to be."<ref name=trio>Moss, Corey (January 5, 2005) [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1495325/01052005/mayer_john.jhtml "John Mayer Plans To 'Close Up Shop On Acoustic Sensitive'"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050222090731/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1495325/01052005/mayer_john.jhtml |date=February 22, 2005 }}. MTV. Retrieved April 12, 2006.</ref>

Around this time Mayer announced that he was "closing up shop on acoustic sensitivity".<ref name=trio/> In the spring of 2005, Mayer formed the John Mayer Trio with bassist [[Pino Palladino]] and drummer [[Steve Jordan (musician)|Steve Jordan]], both of whom he had met through studio sessions. The trio combined blues and rock music. In October 2005, they opened for [[the Rolling Stones]]<ref>Moss Corey (September 16, 2005). [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1509723/20050916/mayer_john.jhtml "John Mayer Trio Geek Out With Live Album, Rolling Stones Jokes"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001032146/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1509723/20050916/mayer_john.jhtml |date=October 1, 2007 }}. MTV. Retrieved June 8, 2007.</ref> and that November released a live album called ''[[Try!]]'' The band took a break in mid-2006.{{Clear}}

[[File:John Mayer live in 2007 01.png|thumb|left|Mayer performing in San Jose, California, June 2007]]
Mayer's third studio album, titled ''[[Continuum (John Mayer album)|Continuum]]'', was released on September 12, 2006, produced by Mayer and [[Steve Jordan (musician)|Steve Jordan]]. Mayer suggested the album was intended to combine blues and pop. In that vein, two of the tracks from his Trio release ''Try!''—"Vultures" and "Gravity"—were included on ''Continuum''.<ref name=ELLE/> Despite his excitement, in a ''Rolling Stone'' interview, Mayer recalled that after former Columbia Records head [[Don Ienner]] panned ''Continuum'' he briefly considered quitting music and studying design full-time.<ref name=RS06/>

The first single from ''Continuum'' was "[[Waiting on the World to Change]]", which debuted on ''[[The Ron and Fez Show]]''. The song was the third-most downloaded song of the week on the [[iTunes Store]] following its release on July 11, 2006,{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} and debuted at number 25 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] Chart.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} On August 23, 2006, Mayer debuted the entire album on the Los Angeles radio station [[KYSR|Star 98.7]], offering commentary on each track.<ref>Mayer, John (2006). [http://johnmayer.com/blog/john/200608#83 "Continuum First Listen"] JohnMayer.com. Retrieved June 8, 2007. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141126220122/http://johnmayer.com/blog/john/200608#83 |date=November 26, 2014 }}</ref> A subsequent version was released the next day on the [[Clear Channel Communications|Clear Channel Music]] website as a streaming sneak preview. On September 21, 2006, Mayer appeared on ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]'', playing "Waiting on the World to Change" and "Slow Dancing in a Burning Room". The song "Gravity" was featured on the television series ''[[House (TV series)|House]]'', in the episode "Cane & Able" and ''[[Numb3rs]]''. He recorded a session for the British program ''[[Live from Abbey Road]]'' at [[Abbey Road Studios]] on October 22, 2006.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}

On December 7, 2006, Mayer was nominated for five Grammy Awards, including [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]].<ref>{{Cite web|author=Variety Staff|date=2006-12-07|title=Grammy nominations list (part 1)|url=https://variety.com/2006/film/awards/grammy-nominations-list-part-1-1117955271/|access-date=2021-02-02|website=Variety|language=en-US}}</ref> The Trio received a nomination for ''Try!''. He won two: Best Pop Song with Vocal for "Waiting on the World to Change" and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Album|Best Pop Album]] for ''Continuum''.<ref name=Grammyverification/> Mayer remixed an acoustic version of his single "Waiting on the World to Change" with vocal additions from fellow musician [[Ben Harper]]. In preparation for ''Continuum'', Mayer had booked the [[Village Recorder]] in Los Angeles to record five acoustic versions of his songs with veteran musician [[Robbie McIntosh]]. These recordings became ''[[The Village Sessions]]'', an EP released on December 12, 2006. As usual, Mayer oversaw the artwork.<ref>[http://www.johnmayer.com/news/archive/200612 "'The Village Sessions' Released Today"]. JohnMayer.com. Retrieved June 8, 2007. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110104217/http://www.johnmayer.com/news/archive/200612 |date=November 10, 2014 }}</ref> The initial North American ''Continuum'' tour ended on February 28, 2007, with a show at [[Madison Square Garden]] that the ''[[New York Post]]'' described as "career-defining".<ref name="NYP">Aquilante, Dan (2007). [https://nypost.com/2007/03/02/mayer-a-player-on-big-stage/ "Mayer: A Player On Big Stage"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219050658/http://nypost.com/2007/03/02/mayer-a-player-on-big-stage/ |date=February 19, 2017 }} ''New York Post''. Retrieved March 25, 2015.</ref>

On November 20, 2007, the re-issue of ''Continuum'' became available online and in stores. The release contained a bonus disc of six live songs from his 2007 tour: five from ''Continuum'' and a cover of the [[Ray Charles]] song "[[I Don't Need No Doctor]]".<ref>JohnMayer.org staff [http://www.johnmayer.com/news/archive/200711#2 "Continuum (special edition) to be released on November 20; includes 6 live tracks and new single, ''Say''"]. Retrieved November 19, 2007. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120234840/http://www.johnmayer.com/news/archive/200711#2 |date=January 20, 2015 }}</ref> His single "[[Say (John Mayer song)|Say]]", from the film ''The'' ''Bucket List,'' became available through [[iTunes]].{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} On December 6, 2007, "Belief" was nominated for Best Male Pop Vocal for the [[50th Annual Grammy Awards]]. He accompanied [[Alicia Keys]] on guitar on her song "[[No One (Alicia Keys song)|No One]]" at the ceremony.<ref>[[Josh Tyrangiel|Tyrangiel, Josh]] {{cite journal|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1710840_1710850_1710881,00.html|title=Alicia Keys with John Mayer - The 50th Annual Grammy Awards|date=February 8, 2008|journal=[[Time Magazine|Time]]|access-date=December 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414103058/http://content.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1710840_1710850_1710881,00.html|archive-date=April 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, he was selected by the editors of ''Time'' magazine as one of the [[Time 100|100 Most Influential People of 2007]], listed among artists and entertainers.<ref name=time100>[[Tyrangiel, Josh]] (May 14, 2007) [http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/time100/article/0,28804,1595326_1595332_1616690,00.html "John Mayer"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070505052717/http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/time100/article/0,28804,1595326_1595332_1616690,00.html |date=May 5, 2007 }} ''Time'' '''169''' (20): p. 140.</ref>

In February 2008, Mayer hosted a three-day Caribbean cruise event that included performances with various musicians including [[David Ryan Harris]], [[Brett Dennen]], [[Colbie Caillat]], and [[Dave Barnes]], among others. The event was called "The Mayercraft Carrier" and was held aboard the cruise ship known as the ''[[Carnival Victory]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mayercraftcarrier.com/artists.html|website=MayercraftCarrier.com|access-date=September 26, 2007|title=Mayercraft Carrier Cruise: February 1–4, 2008: A John Mayer/Sixthman Experience|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011001821/http://mayercraftcarrier.com/artists.html|archive-date=October 11, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> A follow-up cruise titled "Mayercraft Carrier 2" sailed from Los Angeles March 27–31, 2009, on the [[Carnival Splendor]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=John Mayer Talks Oscars, 'Mayercraft Carrier 2' & Britney Spears|url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/local/john_mayer_talks_oscars___mayercraft_carrier_2____britney_spears/1866311/|access-date=2021-02-02|website=NBC4 Washington|language=en-US}}</ref>

On July 1, 2008, Mayer released ''[[Where the Light Is: John Mayer Live in Los Angeles|Where the Light Is]]'', a live concert film of Mayer's performance at the Nokia Theatre [[L.A. Live]] on December 8, 2007.<ref name="RS where the light is">{{cite magazine|last=Kemp|first=Mark|title=Where The Light Is: John Mayer Live In Los Angeles - Albums Reviews|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/where-the-light-is-john-mayer-live-in-los-angeles-20080701|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=December 23, 2013|date=July 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140324035227/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/where-the-light-is-john-mayer-live-in-los-angeles-20080701|archive-date=March 24, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The film was directed by [[Danny Clinch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnmayer.com/blog#1952|title=DVD Shoot|author=Mayer, John |website=JohnMayer.com |date=November 26, 2007 |access-date=December 29, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071229095313/http://www.johnmayer.com/blog#1952|archive-date=December 29, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> It features Mayer opening with an acoustic set, followed by a blues set with the Trio and concluded by a full set with the band from the ''Continuum'' album.<ref name="billboard blackberry">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1045927/mayer-aligns-with-blackberry-for-summer-tour|title=Mayer Aligns With Blackberry For Summer Tour|author=Waddell, Ray|magazine=Billboard|date=April 7, 2008|access-date=April 8, 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506181919/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1045927/mayer-aligns-with-blackberry-for-summer-tour| archive-date= May 6, 2008 | url-status=live}}</ref>

===''Battle Studies'' (2009)===
{{main|Battle Studies (album)}}
Australian artist [[Guy Sebastian]] invited Mayer to collaborate on three songs from his 2009 album ''[[Like It Like That (album)|Like It Like That]]''.<ref>Cashmere, Paul (August 3, 2009), [http://www.undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=8910 "Guy Sebastian Album To Be Released In October"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091016133045/http://www.undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=8910 |date=October 16, 2009 }}. ''Undercover Music News''. Retrieved August 4, 2009.</ref> Mayer also played guitar on the title track of [[Crosby Loggins]]' debut LP, ''Time to Move''.<ref>Newman-Bremang, Kathleen (May 12, 2009), [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1611223/20090512/mraz_jason.jhtml "Crosby Loggins Nabs John Mayer, Kara DioGuardi For Debut Album'Rock the Cradle' winner plans to drop Time to Move in July"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515132254/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1611223/20090512/mraz_jason.jhtml |date=May 15, 2009 }}. MTV. Retrieved June 24, 2009.</ref>

On July 7, 2009, Mayer performed an instrumental guitar version of [[Michael Jackson]]'s "[[Human Nature (Michael Jackson song)|Human Nature]]" at Jackson's televised [[Michael Jackson memorial service|memorial service]].<ref>Powers, Ann; Martens, Todd (July 7, 2009), [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2009/07/michael-jackson-memorial-john-mayer-performs-human-nature.html "Michael Jackson memorial: John Mayer performs 'Human Nature'"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204035742/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2009/07/michael-jackson-memorial-john-mayer-performs-human-nature.html |date=February 4, 2017 }}. ''Los Angeles Times'' blog. Retrieved July 8, 2009.</ref> He co-wrote "World of Chances" with [[Demi Lovato]] for Lovato's second album ''[[Here We Go Again (Demi Lovato album)|Here We Go Again]]'', released later that month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1616552/demi-lovato-gets-personal-on-here-we-go-again.jhtml|title=Demi Lovato Gets Personal on Here We Go Again|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|date=July 21, 2009|website=MTV News|access-date=April 3, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216012158/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1616552/demi-lovato-gets-personal-on-here-we-go-again.jhtml|archive-date=February 16, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>

After the overwhelming success of ''Continuum'', Mayer confessed to be intimidated with beginning on a follow-up. However, he stated, "I think it got a lot easier when I realized that no matter what I do, it's not going to be ''Continuum'', good or bad."<ref name=micktaylor/> On November 17, 2009, Mayer's fourth studio album, ''[[Battle Studies (album)|Battle Studies]]'', debuted at number one on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] album chart.<ref>SISARIO, BEN (November 26, 2009), "John Mayer Is No. 1 in Pre-Holiday Week". ''The New York Times''. :2.</ref> The first single, "[[Who Says (John Mayer song)|Who Says]]", was released on September 24, 2009, in advance of the album, followed on October 19 by "[[Heartbreak Warfare]]" and "[[Half of My Heart]]" on June 21, 2010. The accompanying arena tour grossed {{USD}}45 million.<ref name=DIEHL/> Despite the album's commercial success, critics reactions were mixed. Some reviews glowed, calling it his "most adventurous",<ref>Graff, Gary (November 14, 2009), "Battle Studies". ''Billboard''. '''121''' (45):32.</ref><ref>Arnold, Chuck (November 30, 2009), "Battle Studies". ''People''.'''72''' (22): p. 49.</ref> others called the album "safe" and noted that "Mayer the singer-songwriter and Mayer the man about town sometimes seem disconnected, like they don't even belong in the same body".<ref name=Hedegaard/><ref>Jerry Shriver; Elysa Gardner; [[Edna Gundersen]] (November 17, 2009), "Albums". ''USA Today''.</ref><ref>Greenblatt, Leah (November 20, 2009), "Battle Studies".'' Entertainment Weekly''. (1076):84.</ref><ref>Keefe, Jonathan (November 22, 2009), [https://slantmagazine.com/music/review/john-mayer-battle-studies/1918 "John Mayer – Battle Studies"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100205082449/http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/john-mayer-battle-studies/1918 |date=February 5, 2010 }}. ''Slant''. Retrieved February 8, 2010.</ref> Mayer admitted to ''Rolling Stone'' that he thought ''Battle Studies'' was not his best album.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/john-mayers-dirty-mind-lonely-heart-new-issue-of-rolling-stone-20100119|title=John Mayer's Dirty Mind Lonely Heart|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=January 19, 2010|access-date=July 24, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713014502/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/john-mayers-dirty-mind-lonely-heart-new-issue-of-rolling-stone-20100119|archive-date=July 13, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinkisthenewblog.com/2010/01/john-mayer-does-rolling-stone-magazine|title=John Mayer Does 'Rolling Stone' Magazine|website=Pink is the New Blog|date=January 20, 2010|access-date=July 24, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715085059/http://www.pinkisthenewblog.com/2010/01/john-mayer-does-rolling-stone-magazine/|archive-date=July 15, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Personal troubles and hiatus (2010–2013)===
{{see also|Born and Raised (John Mayer album)}}

{{quote box|width=350px|align=right|quote=I did a lot of therapy, like anti-acid reflux, and it didn't work, then I went on vocal rest. No alcohol. No spicy food. No talking. Most of September I wasn't talking at all. I'd have a Bluetooth keyboard, and someone would have an iPad to read what I type. I had to point to menus at restaurants.|source=John Mayer<ref name="mayer silent">{{cite web|title=John Mayer: 'I was silent for a month' |url=http://blog.sfgate.com/dailydish/2012/06/11/john-mayer-%E2%80%98i-was-silent-for-a-month%E2%80%99/|website=San Francisco Chronicle| date=June 11, 2012| access-date=June 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612201357/http://blog.sfgate.com/dailydish/2012/06/11/john-mayer-%e2%80%98i-was-silent-for-a-month%e2%80%99/|archive-date=June 12, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>}} Following two revealing and highly controversial magazine interviews in February 2010 with ''Rolling Stone'' and ''Playboy'' magazines,<ref name=outrage/> Mayer withdrew from public life and ceased giving interviews. While still on tour for ''Battle Studies'', he began work in earnest on his fifth studio album—which drew on the popular music of [[Laurel Canyon, Los Angeles#History|Laurel Canyon]] in the early 1970s.<ref name=sniping>Wood, Mikael (August 15, 2013), [https://latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-mn-mayer-swift-personal-20130818-story.html#page=1 "Musical sniping, a la John Mayer and Taylor Swift"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411165722/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-mn-mayer-swift-personal-20130818-story.html#page=1 |date=April 11, 2015 }}. ''Los Angeles Times''. Retrieved March 25, 2015.</ref> Around this time, he began to experience vocal problems, and sought medical assistance.<ref name=DIEHL>{{cite magazine| last= Diehl| first= Matt | date= March 30, 2013|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1554215/john-mayer-the-billboard-cover-story |title= Breaking the Silence| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409093418/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1554215/john-mayer-the-billboard-cover-story |archive-date= April 9, 2015 | magazine= Billboard| volume= 125| number= 12| pages= 30–35}}</ref> On September 16, 2011, he posted on his blog that his next record, ''Born and Raised,'' would be delayed due to treatment he was receiving for a [[granuloma]] discovered on his vocal cords.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Matthew Perpetua |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/john-mayer-diagnosed-with-throat-condition-20110919 |title=John Mayer Diagnosed With Throat Condition |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=September 19, 2011 |access-date=April 16, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429102422/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/john-mayer-diagnosed-with-throat-condition-20110919 |archive-date= April 29, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Mayer described the event as a "temporary setback" and added that the album was entirely finished except for a few vocal tracks.<ref>Levy, Daniel S. (October 3, 2011), "Passages".''People''. '''76''' (13):76.</ref> A month later, on October 20, 2011, Mayer posted, "I had surgery this afternoon to remove it and am now on complete vocal rest for a month or more," during which he planned to "travel the country, look, and listen".<ref>Fowler, Brandi (October 23, 2011), [http://www.eonline.com/news/271064/john-mayer-has-surgery-to-heal-vocal-cords "John Mayer Has Surgery to Heal Vocal Cords"] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403171340/http://www.eonline.com/news/271064/john-mayer-has-surgery-to-heal-vocal-cords |date=April 3, 2015 }}. ''E!''. Retrieved March 23, 2015.</ref> However, the surgery did not work as expected, and he had to undergo another one that August.<ref name= "mayer silent" /><ref name=patrickdoyle>Doyle, Patrick (January 30, 2013), [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/q-a-john-mayer-on-his-new-voice-summer-tour-and-dating-katy-perry-20130130#ixzz3UqmCmNvs Q&A: John Mayer on His New Voice, Summer Tour and Dating Katy Perry] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903121602/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/q-a-john-mayer-on-his-new-voice-summer-tour-and-dating-katy-perry-20130130#ixzz3UqmCmNvs |date=September 3, 2017 }}. ''Rolling Stone''. Retrieved March 19, 2015.</ref> During his travels, he visited and fell in love with [[Bozeman, Montana]], where he bought a house and re-settled in the spring of 2012.<ref name="ellen" /><ref name="Missoula Independent">Browning, Skylar (May 15, 2012), [http://missoulanews.bigskypress.com/IndyBlog/archives/2012/05/15/john-mayer-now-lives-in-montana "John Mayer now lives in Montana"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927065526/http://missoulanews.bigskypress.com/IndyBlog/archives/2012/05/15/john-mayer-now-lives-in-montana |date=September 27, 2012 }}. ''Missoula Independent''. Retrieved June 1, 2012.</ref><ref name="CBS Sunday morning">{{cite web|title=John Mayer: His "Shadow Days" Are Over"|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/john-mayer-his-shadow-days-are-over/|publisher=CBS news|access-date=February 10, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218183037/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/john-mayer-his-shadow-days-are-over/|archive-date=December 18, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:The Rolling Stones with John Mayer, Prudential Center 2012-12-13.jpg|thumb|left|240px|Mayer on stage with [[The Rolling Stones]] at the [[Prudential Center]], New Jersey, December 13, 2012]]
With his treatments complete, Mayer finished the vocals on ''Born and Raised'',<ref name=DIEHL/> and the album's first single, "Shadow Days", was released on February 27, 2012. The following day, he released the track listing for the album, announcing that it would be released on May 22 of that year.<ref name="born and raised track listing">{{cite web|url=http://johnmayer.com/news/news-18431927036/ |title=News |website=John Mayer |access-date=April 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503033911/http://johnmayer.com/news/news-18431927036/ |archive-date=May 3, 2012 }}</ref> He described it as his "most honest" album,<ref name="ellen" /> and begin booking dates at more "intimate" venues than for ''Battle Studies''.<ref name=DIEHL/> He also accepted an invitation to appear at the [[South by Southwest]] festival.<ref name=DIEHL/> However, the granuloma returned, and on March 9, 2012, Mayer announced that he had been forced to cancel his tour and refrain from all singing indefinitely.<ref>Oldenburg, Ann (March 9, 2012), [http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2012/03/john-mayer-cancels-tour-takes-indefinite-hiatus/1 "John Mayer cancels tour, takes 'indefinite hiatus'"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310125955/http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2012/03/john-mayer-cancels-tour-takes-indefinite-hiatus/1 |date=March 10, 2012 }}. ''USA TODAY''. Retrieved March 18, 2015.</ref> Even so, ''Born and Raised'' was released as scheduled, and entered the ''Billboard'' 200 chart at number one, selling 219,000 copies in its first week.<ref name=DIEHL/> It also received generally positive critical feedback; ''Rolling Stone'' rated it number 17 on its list of the 50 Best Albums of 2012,<ref>{{cite magazine|last=''Rolling Stone'' staff|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-albums-of-2012-20121205/john-mayer-born-and-raised-19691231|title=John Mayer, 'Born and Raised' |date=December 5, 2012|access-date=March 25, 2015|magazine=Rolling Stone|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150331060151/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-albums-of-2012-20121205/john-mayer-born-and-raised-19691231 |archive-date=March 31, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and ''People'' magazine called it "a shimmering album".<ref>Arnold, Chuck (May 28, 2012), [http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20596474,00.html "John Mayer's "Born and Raised" Is a Perfect Road Trip Album: Review"] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402161554/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20596474,00.html |date=April 2, 2015 }}, ''People''. '''77''' (22):47.</ref> Meanwhile, Mayer brought a new focus to his guitar playing and, fearing that his vocal cords had been permanently damaged, tried to come to terms with a possible future as a [[session musician]].<ref name=DIEHL/> Determined to be cured, he sought help from the [[UCLA]] Voice Center.<ref name=DIEHL/> That September, [[otolaryngologist]] Dr. Gerald Berke paralyzed Mayer's vocal cords with a series of high-dose [[Botox#Medical uses|Botox]] injections, hoping that they would allow the granuloma to heal.<ref name=DIEHL/> Mayer's vocal rest extended to several months and,<ref>{{cite web|last=Oldenburg|first=Ann|title=After more throat surgery, John Mayer takes vow of silence |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2012/09/after-more-throat-surgery-john-mayer-takes-vow-of-silence/1|website=USA Today| access-date=February 18, 2013|date=September 4, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130214121203/http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2012/09/after-more-throat-surgery-john-mayer-takes-vow-of-silence/1|archive-date=February 14, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> unable to even talk, his performances were limited to accompanying other artists on guitar. He appeared in September 2012 on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', where he joined musical guest [[Frank Ocean]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Markman|first=Rob|title=Frank Ocean's Big Weekend: 'SNL' Debut And A Brand-New Video|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1693922/frank-ocean-snl-pyramids-single.jhtml |website=MTV.com |access-date=February 18, 2013|date=September 17, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121123134756/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1693922/frank-ocean-snl-pyramids-single.jhtml|archive-date=November 23, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> He played with the [[Rolling Stones]] in New Jersey in December 2012.<ref name=DIEHL/>

By January 2013, Mayer had recovered sufficiently enough to perform at a benefit concert in Bozeman, after almost two years without singing publicly.<ref name="benefitconcert">{{cite web|last=Hergett|first=Rachel|title=Welcome home|url=http://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/news/article_263a856c-606e-11e2-9626-001a4bcf887a.html|website=The Bozeman Daily Chronicle |access-date=February 18, 2013 |date=January 16, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120143224/http://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/news/article_263a856c-606e-11e2-9626-001a4bcf887a.html|archive-date=January 20, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2013, he made an appearance at the [[Crossroads Guitar Festival]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Harp|first=Justin|title=John Mayer, Jeff Beck join Eric Clapton's Crossroads festival |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a441917/john-mayer-jeff-beck-join-eric-claptons-crossroads-festival.html|website=[[Digital Spy]] |access-date= February 18, 2013|date=November 29, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130214065833/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a441917/john-mayer-jeff-beck-join-eric-claptons-crossroads-festival.html |archive-date=February 14, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> and at the 28th Annual [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] Induction Ceremony, where he inducted the late [[Albert King]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Graff|first=Gary|title=Foo Fighters, Don Henley, John Mayer Lead 2013 Rock Hall Presenters|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/record-labels/1521511/foo-fighters-don-henley-john-mayer-lead-2013-rock-hall| magazine= Billboard |access-date=February 18, 2013|date=January 23, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130204072239/http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/record-labels/1521511/foo-fighters-don-henley-john-mayer-lead-2013-rock-hall|archive-date=February 4, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> A show at the [[Tuscaloosa Amphitheater]] in Alabama on April 25, 2013, followed by a set at the [[New Orleans Jazz & Heritage Festival]] the next day, marked his first full-length concerts since his health troubles.<ref name= DIEHL/><ref>{{cite web|last=Barton|first=Chris|title=Fleetwood Mac and Frank Ocean lead New Orleans Jazz Fest lineup |url=https://latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-frank-ocean-wayne-shorter-new-orleans-jazz-fest-20130117,0,6757985.story|website=Los Angeles Times| access-date=February 18, 2013|date=January 17, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130131171944/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-frank-ocean-wayne-shorter-new-orleans-jazz-fest-20130117,0,6757985.story|archive-date=January 31, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>Hughes Cobb, Mark (April 26, 2013), [http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20130426/news/130429796 "John Mayer starts off season at Tuscaloosa Amphitheater"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402222743/http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20130426/news/130429796 |date=April 2, 2015 }}, ''Tuscaloosa News''. Retrieved March 20, 2015.</ref>

===''Paradise Valley'', Dead & Company, ''The Search for Everything'' (2013–2018)===
{{main|Paradise Valley (album)|Dead & Company|The Search for Everything}}
[[File:John Mayer at the Barclays Center.jpeg|thumbnail|Mayer performing at the [[Barclays Center]] in [[Brooklyn, New York]], on December 17, 2013]]
In June 2013, Mayer announced that he was finishing work on his sixth album, ''[[Paradise Valley (album)|Paradise Valley]].''<ref>{{cite web|date=June 18, 2013|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10151686223176252&set=a.157882861251.115273.5295171251&type=1|title=It's official. the new album is Paradise Valley|website=Facebook|access-date=June 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017085446/https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10151686223176252&set=a.157882861251.115273.5295171251&type=1|archive-date=October 17, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Produced by [[Don Was]], the album features "low-key folk-rock tunes".<ref name=sniping/><ref name=VOZICK>VOZICK-LEVINSON, SIMON (September 12, 2013), [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/john-mayer-swears-hes-done-with-the-fame-game-20130830 "John Mayer Swears He's Done With the Fame Game] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827130254/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/john-mayer-swears-hes-done-with-the-fame-game-20130830 |date=August 27, 2017 }}". ''Rolling Stone''. (1191):16.</ref> He collaborated with [[Frank Ocean]] on the song "Wildfire Pt. 2",<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Coulehan|first=Eric|title=New John Mayer Album Features Katy Perry, Frank Ocean|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/new-john-mayer-album-features-katy-perry-frank-ocean-20130808|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=December 24, 2013|date=August 8, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020122507/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/new-john-mayer-album-features-katy-perry-frank-ocean-20130808|archive-date=October 20, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> and with [[Katy Perry]] on "[[Who You Love]]".<ref name=ParadiseNow>{{cite magazine|last=Danton|first=Eric R.|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/listen-to-john-mayers-paradise-valley-now-20130813|title=Listen to John Mayer's 'Paradise Valley' Now|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=August 13, 2013|date=August 13, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130816040801/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/listen-to-john-mayers-paradise-valley-now-20130813|archive-date=August 16, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The latter song would go on to become the album's third single, and an accompanying music video was released on December 17.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Miller|first=Julie|title=Exclusive: John Mayer and Katy Perry's First Portraits Together, Commemorating Their 'Who You Love' Single|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/online/oscars/2013/12/john-mayer-katy-perry-who-you-love-artwork_slideshow_item4_5|magazine=Vanity Fair|date=December 2, 2013|access-date=December 3, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205010559/http://www.vanityfair.com/online/oscars/2013/12/john-mayer-katy-perry-who-you-love-artwork_slideshow_item4_5|archive-date=December 5, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> On June 18, 2013, he released a lyric video for the album's first single, "Paper Doll", on his official YouTube page.<ref>{{cite AV media | date = June 18, 2013 | title = John Mayer – Paper Doll (Lyric) | medium = Music video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=565tXd1UyYI | access-date = March 19, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317083308/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=565tXd1UyYI | archive-date = March 17, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref> The album was released August 20, 2013,<ref>Danton, Eric R (August 13, 2013), [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/listen-to-john-mayers-paradise-valley-now-20130813#ixzz3VEHiZNYd "Listen to John Mayer's 'Paradise Valley' Now"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130816040801/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/listen-to-john-mayers-paradise-valley-now-20130813#ixzz3VEHiZNYd |date=August 16, 2013 }}. Retrieved March 23, 2015.</ref> and—meeting with positive reviews<ref name=metacritic>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/paradise-valley/john-mayer/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for Paradise Valley |website=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=August 19, 2013 |access-date=December 24, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207075546/http://www.metacritic.com/music/paradise-valley/john-mayer/critic-reviews |archive-date=December 7, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>—debuted at number two on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart, with first-week sales of 145,560 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitsdailydouble.com/sales/salescht.cgi |title=Building Album Sales Chart |website=HITS Daily Double |access-date=August 28, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915012320/http://www.hitsdailydouble.com/sales/salescht.cgi |archive-date=September 15, 2014 }}</ref> Mayer embarked on a tour, his first in three years, in support of ''Born and Raised'' and ''Paradise Valley''. The American leg of the tour ran from July to December 2013 with [[Interscope Records|Interscope]] recording artist [[Phillip Phillips]] serving as the supporting act.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Schneider|first=Marc|title=John Mayer Announces First Tour in 3 Years|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1554197/john-mayer-announces-first-tour-in-3-years|magazine=Billboard|access-date=December 24, 2013|date=March 21, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108194945/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1554197/john-mayer-announces-first-tour-in-3-years|archive-date=January 8, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|title=Katy Perry, John Mayer Kiss Onstage: Watch Their Live 'Who You Love' Duet|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1719266/katy-perry-john-mayer-onstage-kiss-video.jhtml|work=MTV|access-date=December 24, 2013|date=December 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220210807/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1719266/katy-perry-john-mayer-onstage-kiss-video.jhtml|archive-date=December 20, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The tour visited Australia in April 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bella|first=Sarah|title=John Mayer Announces Headlining Australian Tour Dates, April 2014|url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/john-mayer-announces-headlining-australian-tour-dates-april-2014/|website=Music Feeds|access-date=December 24, 2013|date=October 16, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140123073813/http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/john-mayer-announces-headlining-australian-tour-dates-april-2014/|archive-date=January 23, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>

During a concert in [[Adelaide, Australia|Adelaide]], Mayer covered the Beyoncé song "[[XO (song)#John Mayer version|XO]]" .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/04/15/video-john-mayer-covers-beyonce-xo/|title=John Mayer Covers Beyoncé's 'XO'|work=Rap-Up|date=April 15, 2014|access-date=June 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140806105034/http://www.rap-up.com/2014/04/15/video-john-mayer-covers-beyonce-xo/|archive-date=August 6, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> One month later, on May 22, he released a studio version of the song on his [[SoundCloud]] account.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a573141/john-mayer-unveils-acoustic-cover-of-beyonces-xo.html|title=John Mayer unveils acoustic cover of Beyoncé's 'XO'|publisher=Digital Spy. Hearst Corporation|first=Tom|last=Eames|date=May 23, 2014|access-date=May 23, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523212707/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a573141/john-mayer-unveils-acoustic-cover-of-beyonces-xo.html|archive-date=May 23, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> It was made available for digital download by Columbia Records on May 27, 2014, through the iTunes Store.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/xo-single/id881555962|title=XO – Single by John Mayer|date=May 27, 2014|publisher=iTunes Store. Apple Inc|location=United States|access-date=May 27, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140813072417/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/xo-single/id881555962|archive-date=August 13, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> For the week ending June 1, 2014, Mayer's version debuted at number 90 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart and number 13 on the US [[Hot Rock Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6113840/john-mayers-beyonce-cover-soars-onto-hot-rock-songs-chart|title=John Mayer's Beyonce Cover Soars Onto Hot Rock Songs Chart|last=White|first=Emily|magazine=Billboard|date=June 6, 2014|access-date=June 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140609234805/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6113840/john-mayers-beyonce-cover-soars-onto-hot-rock-songs-chart|archive-date=June 9, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100?page=8 |title=June 14, 2014: The Hot 100 |magazine=Billboard |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140704070039/http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100?page=8 |page=9 |archive-date=July 4, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> On the Canadian Hot 100, "XO" peaked at a position of 76.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=John Mayer Chart History (Canadian Hot 100) |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/john-mayer/chart-history/can/ |magazine=Billboard}}</ref> The single also peaked at number 81 on the Australian Singles Chart (its debut week),<ref>{{cite web|first=Gavin|last=Ryan|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/justice-crew-top-aria-singles-for-5th-week-20140607|title=Justice Crew Top ARIA Singles Chart For 5th Week|work=Noise11|publisher=Noise Network|date=June 7, 2014|access-date=June 7, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714221740/http://www.noise11.com/news/justice-crew-top-aria-singles-for-5th-week-20140607|archive-date=July 14, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and at number 95 on the [[Single Top 100|Dutch Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hung |first1=Steffen |title=John Mayer - XO (in Dutch) |url=https://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=John+Mayer&titel=XO&cat=s |website=Dutch Charts}}</ref> In the UK, it peaked at 115 on the UK Singles Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zobbel.de/cluk/140607cluk.txt|title=Chart Log UK: New Entries Update – 7.06.2014 (Week 22)|publisher=zobbel.de. Tobias Zywietz|access-date=July 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714213705/http://www.zobbel.de/cluk/140607cluk.txt|archive-date=July 14, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Mayer recorded the song "[[Come Rain or Come Shine]]" as a duet with [[Barbra Streisand]] for her album ''[[Partners (Barbra Streisand album)|Partners]]'', released in September 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stern|first1=Bradley|title=Barbra Streisand Is Hypnotized By John Mayer's Sexy Guitar Strumming In 'Partners' Album Trailer: Watch|url=http://www.idolator.com/7533843/barbra-streisand-john-mayer-sexy-guitar-duets-album-partners|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|access-date=August 7, 2015|date=September 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kyriazis|first1=Stefan|title=VIDEO EXCLUSIVE: Watch Barbra Streisand and John Mayer record Come Rain Or Come Shine|url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/music/548301/Barbra-Streisand-John-Mayer-video|website=Daily Express|access-date=August 7, 2015|date=December 22, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630005819/http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/music/548301/Barbra-Streisand-John-Mayer-video|archive-date=June 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>

In February 2015, Mayer performed alongside [[Ed Sheeran]] at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Flanagan|first1=Andrew|title=Grammys 2015: Ed Sheeran Performs 'Thinking Out Loud' with Questlove, Herbie Hancock, John Mayer|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/grammys-2015/grammy-performances/6465571/grammys-2015-ed-sheeran-thinking-out-loud-herbie-hancock-john-mayer-questlove|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=August 7, 2015|date=February 8, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150729075854/http://www.billboard.com/articles/grammys-2015/grammy-performances/6465571/grammys-2015-ed-sheeran-thinking-out-loud-herbie-hancock-john-mayer-questlove|archive-date=July 29, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> As of March, Mayer said he was taking break from working on a "deeply personal new album".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Reed|first1=Ryan|title=John Mayer: 'My High-Speed Crash Was an Intellectual One'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/john-mayer-my-high-speed-crash-was-an-intellectual-one-20150309|website=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|date=March 9, 2015|access-date=September 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804234946/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/john-mayer-my-high-speed-crash-was-an-intellectual-one-20150309|archive-date=August 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Mayer also recounted that in 2011 he happened upon a song by the [[Grateful Dead]] while listening to [[Pandora Radio|Pandora]], and that soon the band's music was all he would listen to.<ref name=deadtour>{{cite magazine|title = John Mayer Talks Grateful Dead Legacy, Fare Thee Well and Learning to Play 'A Universe of Great Songs'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grateful-dead/6655956/john-mayer-grateful-dead-and-company-interview|magazine = Billboard|date = August 5, 2015|access-date = November 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151114163602/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grateful-dead/6655956/john-mayer-grateful-dead-and-company-interview|archive-date = November 14, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2015, while guest hosting ''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]'', Mayer invited Grateful Dead guitar player [[Bob Weir]] to join him in a studio performance. While Weir, [[Phil Lesh]], [[Mickey Hart]] and [[Bill Kreutzmann]] (surviving members of the Grateful Dead) were preparing for their [[Fare Thee Well: Celebrating 50 Years of the Grateful Dead]] tour with [[Trey Anastasio]], Mayer began practicing the band's catalog of songs. That August, Mayer, Weir, Kreutzmann, and Hart formed the group [[Dead & Company]], along with [[Jeff Chimenti]] and [[Oteil Burbridge]], and began a fall tour in the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Halperin|first1=Shirley|title=The Grateful Dead Is Resurrected Once More, This Time With John Mayer: Exclusive|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grateful-dead/6655898/grateful-dead-john-mayer-show-tour|magazine=Billboard|access-date=August 7, 2015|date=August 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150807063753/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grateful-dead/6655898/grateful-dead-john-mayer-show-tour|archive-date=August 7, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The tour was well received (''Billboard'' called it "magical"),<ref name= NYT-Launch16/> and they continued to tour the US into 2016.<ref name=NYT-Launch16/> Although Lesh has declined to join Dead & Company, Mayer also performed with [[Phil Lesh and Friends]] at Terrapin Crossroads in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=John MAyer with Phil Lesh & Friends at Terrapin Crossroads |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/john-mayer-with-phil-lesh-friends-at-terrapin-crossroads |website=Jambase |access-date=September 10, 2018 |date=August 6, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828071145/https://www.jambase.com/article/john-mayer-with-phil-lesh-friends-at-terrapin-crossroads |archive-date=August 28, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>

As a result of his touring with Dead & Company, Mayer postponed working on his next studio album until January 2016, with plans to finish it by the end of the year.<ref>{{cite news|title=John Mayer grateful for his time with Dead & Company|url=http://www.sacbee.com/entertainment/music-news-reviews/article92189277.html|newspaper=The Sacramento Bee|access-date=July 29, 2016|last1=Sculley|first1=Alan|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923105650/http://www.sacbee.com/entertainment/music-news-reviews/article92189277.html|archive-date=September 23, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On November 17, 2016, Mayer released "[[Love on the Weekend]]" as the lead single from his EP ''[[The Search for Everything: Wave One]]'', which was then released on January 20, 2017.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Danielle Jackson|url=https://ew.com/music/2017/01/03/john-mayer-release-plans-new-music/|title=John Mayer announces release plans for new music|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=January 3, 2017|access-date=May 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322204617/http://ew.com/music/2017/01/03/john-mayer-release-plans-new-music/|archive-date=March 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A second EP, ''[[The Search for Everything: Wave Two]]'', was released on February 24, 2017, along with the single "Still Feel Like Your Man". The album ''[[The Search for Everything]]'' was released on April 14, 2017 and was promoted by a third single titled "In the Blood", released on May 1, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|title=John Mayer - In the Blood (Radio Edit)|url=http://daily.plaympe.com/john-mayer-in-the-blood-radio-edit/|publisher=Daily Play MPE|access-date=May 3, 2017|date=May 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507160950/http://daily.plaympe.com/john-mayer-in-the-blood-radio-edit/|archive-date=May 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=John Mayer ships "In the Blood" to country studio|url=http://theboot.com/john-mayer-country-single-in-the-blood/|publisher=The Boot|access-date=April 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419121030/http://theboot.com/john-mayer-country-single-in-the-blood/|archive-date=April 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and by [[The Search for Everything World Tour]] from March to October of the same year.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/john-mayer-maps-out-search-for-everything-world-tour-w463576|title=John Mayer Maps Out 'Search for Everything' World Tour|last1=Kreps|first1=Daniel|date=January 30, 2017|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=Wenner Media LLC|access-date=May 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516162922/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/john-mayer-maps-out-search-for-everything-world-tour-w463576|archive-date=May 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>

Mayer also continued touring with Dead & Company during the [[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2017|summer]]<ref name=Dead2017>{{cite web |url=http://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-announces-summer-tour-2017 |title=Dead & Company Announce Summer Tour 2017 |work=Jam Base |date=December 1, 2016 |access-date=February 24, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203151802/http://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-announces-summer-tour-2017 |archive-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Dead & Company Fall Tour 2017|fall]]<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Dead & Company detail fall tour|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/dead-company-detail-fall-tour-w501739|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=September 7, 2017|date=September 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225174116/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/dead-company-detail-fall-tour-w501739|archive-date=December 25, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> of 2017. On December 5, during the Fall Tour, his appendix burst, resulting in an emergency [[appendectomy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2017/12/05/entertainment/john-mayer-appendectomy/index.html|title=John Mayer recovering from emergency appendectomy|last1=Gonzales|first1=Sandra|date=December 6, 2017|website=[[CNN]]|access-date=April 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409110211/https://edition.cnn.com/2017/12/05/entertainment/john-mayer-appendectomy/index.html|archive-date=April 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and the postponement of the remaining tour dates to February 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-announces-2018-tour-dates|title=Dead & Company Announces New Dates For Postponed Shows|work=JamBase|date=December 8, 2017|access-date=April 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409171541/https://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-announces-2018-tour-dates|archive-date=April 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2018, Dead & Company announced their [[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2018]].<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Wandera|last=Hussein|date=January 18, 2018|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8094919/dead-and-company-tour-2018-dates|title=Dead & Company Announce 19-City Summertime Tour|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180118164256/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8094919/dead-and-company-tour-2018-dates|archive-date=January 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== ''Sob Rock'' (2018–present) ===
{{main|Sob Rock}}
On May 10, 2018, Mayer released the single "[[New Light (John Mayer song)|New Light]]", co-produced by [[No I.D.]] and Mayer himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/john-mayer-and-no-id-share-new-song-new-light-listen/|title=John Mayer and No I.D. Share New Song "New Light": Listen|last1=Kim|first1=Michelle|date=May 10, 2018|website=[[Pitchfork (magazine)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=May 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511081207/https://pitchfork.com/news/john-mayer-and-no-id-share-new-song-new-light-listen/|archive-date=May 11, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with [[Zane Lowe]] for [[Apple Music]] on the release day, he announced "more new music" for 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bhbpo5Bv4Vs|title=John Mayer: 'New Light' Premiere &#124; Beats 1 &#124; Apple Music|date=May 10, 2018|via=YouTube|access-date=May 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180531154744/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bhbpo5Bv4Vs|archive-date=May 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> During his performance at the iHeartRadio Theater on October 24, 2018, he premiered a song titled "I Guess I Just Feel Like".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8481727/john-mayer-new-song-i-guess-i-just-feel-like-listen-iheartradio-theater-concert-recap|title=John Mayer Debuts New Song 'I Guess I Just Feel Like,' Plus More Highlights From LA iHeartRadio Theater Set|last1=Atkinson|first1=Katie|date=October 25, 2018|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=December 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217135807/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8481727/john-mayer-new-song-i-guess-i-just-feel-like-listen-iheartradio-theater-concert-recap|archive-date=December 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On December 12, 2018, he announced a world tour for 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/109277264/john-mayer-kicks-off-world-tour-in-new-zealand|title=John Mayer to kick off world tour in New Zealand, 2019|date=December 12, 2018|website=[[stuff.co.nz]]|access-date=December 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215223154/https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/109277264/john-mayer-kicks-off-world-tour-in-new-zealand|archive-date=December 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Mayer released two singles in 2019; the previously played "I Guess I Just Feel Like" on February 22, and "Carry Me Away" on September 6.

During an episode of John Mayer's show "Current Mood" on March 15, 2020, he revealed that he was in the process of writing and recording songs for a new album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://liveforlivemusic.com/news/john-mayer-coronavirus-anxiety-quarantines-current-mood/|title=John Mayer Talks New Album, Anxiety, COVID-19, More Live On 'Current Mood' [Watch]|work=Live For Live Music|last=Kawas|first=Kel|date=March 16, 2020|access-date=October 7, 2020}}</ref> In early 2021, he stated that the album was completely finished as he began posting snippets of new songs on [[TikTok]] ahead of release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://liveforlivemusic.com/news/john-mayer-new-album-preview-tiktok/|title=John Mayer Shares Preview Of New Album On TikTok [Watch]|work=Live For Live Music|last=O'Brien|first=Andrew|date=March 28, 2021|access-date=March 28, 2021}}</ref> In an interview with [[Kerwin Frost]], Mayer hinted at an April release for the album.<ref>Archived at [https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211211/iWgyprxp1wk Ghostarchive]{{cbignore}} and the [https://web.archive.org/web/20210320112039/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iWgyprxp1wk Wayback Machine]{{cbignore}}: {{Citation|title=KERWIN FROST TALKS TO JOHN MAYER|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iWgyprxp1wk|language=en|access-date=2021-04-04}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Later, the date was pushed back. On June 1, 2021, Mayer officially announced his eighth album ''[[Sob Rock]]'' and on June 4, released the lead single, "[[Last Train Home (John Mayer song)|Last Train Home]]" along with an accompanying music video. The album was released on July 16, 2021 as well as a music video for the song, "Shot In The Dark". The track list included previously released singles "New Light", "I Guess I Just Feel Like" and "Carry Me Away". "Carry Me Away" was slightly reworked production-wise to fit the album’s 1980s aesthetic.

== Touring ==
Mayer began touring as a solo artist in 2001.<ref>Shaw, Lucy (February 28, 2002), "ON THE ROAD". ''Rolling Stone''. (890):25.</ref> While his early records were largely acoustic, early reviewers noted his unexpected electric "guitar heroics" during live performances.<ref name="gavinedwards">Edwards, Gavin (August 22, 2002), "John Mayer". ''Rolling Stone''. (903):28.</ref>

Mayer has toured North America, Europe and Australia<ref name="BT">Sinclair, David (2007). [http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/music-gigs/features/article2167383.ece "John Mayer: My Atlantic crossing"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/2012.12.09-032446/http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/music-gigs/features/article2167383.ece |date=December 9, 2012}} ''The Belfast Telegraph''. Retrieved January 28, 2007.</ref> with many musical groups, including [[Maroon 5]],<ref name=RS>Dansby, Andrew (2004). [https://web.archive.org/web/20070212132837/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/johnmayer/articles/story/5937015/mayer_maroon_5_hit_the_road "Mayer, Maroon 5 Hit the Road"], ''Rolling Stone''. Retrieved April 12, 2006.</ref><ref name="summer 2004">{{cite web|title=John Mayer Summer Tour Dates Announced|url=http://sony.mediaroom.com/2004-03-30-John-Mayer-Summer-Tour-Dates-Announced|publisher=Sony Music|date=March 30, 2004|access-date=June 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614021359/http://sony.mediaroom.com/2004-03-30-John-Mayer-Summer-Tour-Dates-Announced|archive-date=June 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>[[Counting Crows]],<ref name=RoSt>Dansby, Andrew (2003). [https://web.archive.org/web/20070212132747/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/johnmayer/articles/story/5936057/mayer_crows_to_tour "Mayer, Crows to Tour "] ''Rolling Stone''. Retrieved April 12, 2006.</ref><ref name="Mayer Crows">{{cite magazine|title=Mayer Flies With Crows For Summer Tour|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/71677/mayer-flies-with-crows-for-summer-tour|magazine=Billboard|date=April 4, 2003|access-date=June 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614103744/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/71677/mayer-flies-with-crows-for-summer-tour|archive-date=June 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Ben Folds]], [[the Wallflowers]], [[Sheryl Crow]], [[Colbie Caillat]] and [[Train (band)|Train]].<ref name="Mayer Crow">AP staff (June 15, 2006). [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/58131/crow-mayer-teaming-for-tour "Crow, Mayer Teaming For Tour"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524193251/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/58131/crow-mayer-teaming-for-tour |date=May 24, 2013 }}. ''Billboard''. Retrieved May 31, 2007.</ref> In 2010, Mayer and [[Keith Urban]] performed at a [[CMT Crossroads]] concert a medley of their songs and a rendition of [[George Michael]]'s single "Faith".<ref>{{cite web|title=CMT Crossroads: John Mayer and Keith Urban Premieres June 18|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/1637815/cmt-crossroads-john-mayer-and-keith-urban-premieres-june-18/|publisher=CMT|access-date=June 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614021303/http://www.cmt.com/news/1637815/cmt-crossroads-john-mayer-and-keith-urban-premieres-june-18/|archive-date=June 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> This performance led to Urban and Mayer teaming up again for future performances, including at the [[CMT Music Awards#2010|2010 CMT Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=On the Scene at the 2010 CMT Music Awards|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/on-the-scene-at-the-2010-cmt-music-awards-20100609/john-mayer-and-keith-urban-62160486|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=June 9, 2010|access-date=June 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614021201/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/on-the-scene-at-the-2010-cmt-music-awards-20100609/john-mayer-and-keith-urban-62160486|archive-date=June 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

Mayer allows [[taper (concert)|audio taping]] and non-commercial trading of those recordings at most of his live performances.<ref name="Local83">[http://www.local-83.com/web/guest/v2policies General Information] Local 83: Listener's Union. Retrieved June 25, 2007. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070611101212/http://www.local-83.com/web/guest/v2policies |date=June 11, 2007}}</ref> Mayer often shows up at small venues unannounced (or with little advance notice) for surprise concerts—occasionally for free or without accepting the performance fee.<ref>''NME'' New York staff (October 15, 2007), [https://www.nme.com/news/nme/31822 "John Mayer plays tiny surprise show in New York"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304201414/http://www.nme.com/news/nme/31822 |date=March 4, 2016}}. ''NME''. Retrieved January 18, 2011.</ref><ref>Kaplan, Michelle (December 6, 2010), [http://yeahnewyork.com/features/john-mayers-surprise-appearance/ "John Mayer’s Surprise Appearance"]. ''Yeah New York''. Retrieved January 18, 2011. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200922070706/http://yeahnewyork.com/features/john-mayers-surprise-appearance/ |date=September 22, 2020 }}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=March 2015}}<ref>(August 9, 2009), [http://www.johnmayer.com/news/permalink/161 "Secret Show Tonight 8/9/09 at LA'S Troubadour!"']. JohnMayer.com. Retrieved January 18, 2011. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101202090114/http://www.johnmayer.com/news/permalink/161 |date=December 2, 2010 }}</ref><ref name="nypost">Page Six staff (June 18, 2010),
[http://www.nypost.com/p/pagesix/mayer_surprise_awes_fans_t6pQ59SdIeWTVNHAjqJ6dP "John Mayer packs Village Underground in just one hour after tweeting about it"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621072929/http://www.nypost.com/p/pagesix/mayer_surprise_awes_fans_t6pQ59SdIeWTVNHAjqJ6dP |date=June 21, 2010 }}. ''New York Post''. Retrieved January 18, 2011.</ref> He has made appearances throughout the Los Angeles, Atlanta, and New York areas, including shows at [[the Laugh Factory]],<ref name="contactmusic">WENN (June 15, 2006). [http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/story/mayer-apologises-to-hewitt_15_06_2006 "Mayer Apologises To Hewitt"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090914095347/http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/story/mayer-apologises-to-hewitt_15_06_2006 |date=September 14, 2009 }}. ContactMusic.com. Retrieved March 23, 2015.</ref> [[Eddie's Attic]],<ref>Swartz, Kristi E., et al. (September 8, 2010), [http://www.accessatlanta.com/atlanta-music/john-mayer-plays-surprise-608750.html "John Mayer plays surprise Eddie's Attic show Tuesday"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405185849/http://www.accessatlanta.com/atlanta-music/john-mayer-plays-surprise-608750.html |date=April 5, 2012}}. ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]''. Retrieved January 18, 2011.</ref> and the Village Underground.<ref name="nypost" /> After a public campaign by their senior class president, Mayer performed a surprise three-song set at the 2004 [[Pennsbury High School]] senior prom.<ref>Scaggs, Austin and Sheffield, Rob (June 24, 2004), "Your Prom Is a Wonderland". ''Rolling Stone''. (951):60.</ref> In June 2015, Mayer appeared as a guest for two nights with [[Phil Lesh and Friends]] at [[Terrapin Crossroads]], recreating the [[Grateful Dead]]'s notable May 8 and June 9, 1977 concerts.<ref>(June 13, 2015), [http://www.jambands.com/news/2015/06/13/john-mayer-helps-phil-lesh-recreate-cornell-77-show-at-terrapin-crossroads "John Mayer 